        <li class="toc-h2"><a href="#the-conscience-is-human">The conscience is human</a></li>
        <li class="toc-h2"><a href="#for-a-collection-like-this-one">For a collection like this one</a></li>
        <li class="toc-h2"><a href="#the-four-surfaces">The surfaces</a></li>
      </ol>
    </nav>
  </aside>

  <%# ── Main prose column ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── %>
  <div class="about-content">

    <h1 id="what-is-enliterator">What is Enliterator?</h1>

    <p class="lede">
      Enliterator confers <strong>literacy</strong> on a collection. Not search — literacy: the capacity to
      participate in inquiry, to accumulate understanding, to compound across visits the way a reader
      compounds across books. A searchable archive can find words. An <em>enliterated</em> collection can
      think about itself.
    </p>

    <%# The page demonstrates its own thesis: it speaks about the collection it's mounted on. %>
    <% if @stats && @stats[:visits].to_i.positive? %>
      <div class="stats-strip">
        <div class="stats-eyebrow">This collection, right now</div>
        <div class="stats-grid">
          <div class="stat-cell">
            <span class="stat-num"><%= number_with_delimiter @stats[:tended_records] %></span>
            <span class="stat-label">records tended</span>
          </div>
          <div class="stat-cell">
            <span class="stat-num"><%= number_with_delimiter @stats[:visits] %></span>
            <span class="stat-label">tending visits</span>
          </div>
          <div class="stat-cell">
            <span class="stat-num"><%= number_with_delimiter @stats[:live_claims] %></span>
            <span class="stat-label">things it knows</span>
          </div>
          <div class="stat-cell">
            <span class="stat-num"><%= @stats[:facets].size %></span>
            <span class="stat-label">facets of inquiry</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <% if @stats[:facets].any? %>
          <div class="stats-facets">
            <span class="facets-label">Active facets:</span>
            <% @stats[:facets].each do |s| %>
              <span class="facet-chip"><%= s %></span>
            <% end %>
          </div>
        <% end %>
        <% if (@stats[:vocab_resolved].to_i + @stats[:vocab_pending].to_i).positive? %>
          <div class="stats-footer">
            Vocabulary: <strong><%= @stats[:vocab_resolved] %></strong> requests resolved &middot;
            <%= @stats[:vocab_pending] %> still open.
            The ontology tends itself — see <%= link_to "Requests", suggestions_path %>.
          </div>
        <% end %>
      </div>
      <p class="muted samples" style="margin-top:.5rem; margin-bottom:1.75rem">
        These numbers are live. Everything below explains how they came to be, and what they become over time.
      </p>
    <% end %>

    <h2 id="the-missing-word">The missing word</h2>
    <p>
      A child is born with the hardware for language, but it sits inert until someone opens the door —
      points at marks, ties them to sounds, ties sounds to the accumulated record of human thought. After
      that door opens, every book changes how they read the next one. Literacy isn't a skill; it's access
      to a loop that <strong>compounds across a lifetime</strong>. We decided that withholding it from a
      child capable of it is not a missing feature — it's neglect.
    </p>
    <p>
      There was no word for the same thing happening to <em>data</em>: a record gaining the capacity to
      participate in meaningful inquiry — not searched once, but <strong>tended</strong>, accumulating
      understanding across visits. So we named it. <strong>Enliteracy</strong>: to put into literacy. The
      prefix does the work — enable, enrich, enlighten. Each is a threshold crossed. This is the door, for
      a collection.
    </p>

    <h2 id="what-tended-means">What "tended" means</h2>
    <p>
      Most systems stop at <em>searchable</em>: embeddings, a vector index, questions in natural language.
      Useful — and the bare minimum. Searchable is to literate what recognizing letters is to reading. You
      can find the words; you don't yet understand the sentences.
    </p>
    <p>
      Enliterator runs a maintenance loop on each record — but the loop runs through a <strong>language
      model</strong>, not a heuristic. A cron job inspects and flags; it never learns. When the loop runs
      through language, each visit brings the whole compressed geometry of human thought to bear on
      <em>this</em> record in <em>this</em> state. The tenth visit isn't smarter because it remembers the
      previous nine — any database remembers. It's smarter because the corpus meets the accumulated history
      of this particular record, and the intersection produces understanding neither contained alone. That
      is what the child gets when the door opens: not a loop of looking at marks, but marks connected to a
      depth of thought no single lifetime could hold. The record gains the same connection.
    </p>

    <h2 id="compounding-attention">Compounding attention — now, and over time</h2>
    <p>
      This is the whole point, so it's worth being precise about what changes the day you turn it on, and
      what changes only with time.
    </p>
    <div class="duo-row">
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-head"><strong>Now</strong> <span class="chip">first pass</span></div>
        <ul>
          <li>A dormant archive becomes <strong>legible</strong>. A record that was only findable becomes
            readable — it carries what it argues, why it matters, who made it, what it connects to.</li>
          <li>The collection gains a <strong>self-portrait</strong>: it knows its own vocabulary, its gaps,
            its shape — and can answer questions grounded in its own records, with provenance.</li>
          <li><strong>First attention</strong> reaches records no curator ever had time for. The triage that
            left most of a collection untouched is no longer forced.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-head"><strong>Over time</strong> <span class="chip">the compounding</span></div>
        <ul>
          <li>Understanding <strong>deepens</strong>, not just persists. Each visit meets the record's
            accumulated history; claims are refined, not duplicated.</li>
          <li>The vocabulary <strong>converges</strong>. Synonyms fold together, noise is rejected, genuine
            new concepts become permanent — the collection's language sharpens toward what actually matters.</li>
          <li>The investment <strong>compounds</strong>. A stronger model or a richer vocabulary re-tends the
            whole collection and lifts all of it at once; cross-record connections thicken into a graph. The
            collection knows more next year than it does today.</li>
          <li>And this is <strong>measured, not assumed</strong>: every record carries its own
            "understanding over time" — visit-by-visit diffs of what it knows — and a blind judge
            compares earlier vs later understanding. If a re-visit merely restates, the system can
            tell; deepening has to be earned.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>
      And the economics flip. When the cost of examining one record drops low enough, the question is no
      longer <em>"can we afford to look at this?"</em> but <em>"can we afford <strong>not</strong> to?"</em>
      A collection of 160,000 works left intellectually dormant was once a resource constraint. When the
      constraint lifts, what remains is a choice.
    </p>

    <h2 id="how-it-works">How it works</h2>
    <p>The machinery, plainly — this is what the engine does today:</p>
    <div class="card">
      <table class="mech-table">
        <tr>
          <td class="mech-key"><strong>Facets are roles</strong></td>
          <td>Each facet of understanding is its own job<%= @stats && @stats[:facets].any? ? " — here: #{@stats[:facets].join(', ')}".html_safe : "" %>. A record is tended once per facet, so "what it argues" and "who wrote it" don't compete in one pass.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="mech-key"><strong>Tiers are capability</strong></td>
          <td>A cheap model does the first pass; the loop escalates to a stronger one only when confidence is low, with a verify floor guarding the result. You pay for capability exactly where it's needed.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="mech-key"><strong>Claims, reconciled</strong></td>
          <td>Each visit proposes claims and reconciles them against what's already known — add, update, delete, or leave alone — so re-tending <em>deepens</em> a record instead of duplicating it. Authoritative host facts are locked and never re-derived.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="mech-key"><strong>A vocabulary that tends itself</strong></td>
          <td>The vocabulary is governed the way a library governs a thesaurus (the Z39.19 discipline): the model can't invent terms — it proposes them by <em>literary warrant</em>. Each reader works with the vocabulary <em>in hand</em> — it sees the candidate terms other readers have already proposed and <strong>affirms</strong> one that fits rather than coining a synonym, so warrant accrues as the breadth of records that recognize a term. An editor — here the <em>considerer</em> — then ratifies a slate (fold synonyms, reject noise, hold genuine new concepts for a human). Approved terms go <strong>live</strong>, and the loop converges on the genuinely contested ones. Authority control as the library has always practiced it: built from reading, distributed across the readers, ratified centrally.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="mech-key"><strong>Collections within collections</strong></td>
          <td>A <em>context</em> is a lens: an item belongs to the whole collection and to any number of labeled sub-collections, each with its own facets and vocabulary, inheriting its ancestors' — the finding-aid principle. An Executive Order is read for its <em>supersession graph</em>; a CRS report for its <em>issue for Congress</em>; neither lens contaminates the other, and within a context a record reads against its fellow members, not the undifferentiated whole.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="mech-key"><strong>Provenance throughout</strong></td>
          <td>Every claim knows how it came to be known — which model, which visit, what it was attributed to. Nothing is asserted without a trail.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="mech-key"><strong>A smoke alarm</strong></td>
          <td>Tending health and spend are visible per facet, so a silent failure can't masquerade as success.</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2 id="the-pulse">The pulse</h2>
    <p>
      For its first fourteen versions this engine was <strong>hand-cranked on purpose</strong> — every pass
      watched, because supervision is how you earn the right to automate. Then we ran the experiment: cohorts
      re-tended under controlled conditions, every diff measured, a blind judge scoring earlier against later.
      The verdict was precise. Re-visiting is safe — but re-reading a record whose surroundings haven't changed
      teaches nothing. What deepens understanding is <em>change</em>: new neighbors tended, a vocabulary that
      grew, a source that moved. And nothing rivals <strong>first attention</strong> — the untended shelf is
      where almost all the learning is.
    </p>
    <p>
      So the heartbeat that replaced the hand-crank is <strong>event-driven, not scheduled</strong>. Each cycle
      it works the untended frontier first, re-reads only the records whose world actually changed, and keeps
      the old "re-tend everything every N days" rule only as a safety net. Two instruments replace the watching
      eye: a <strong>spend cap enforced on actual tokens</strong> — a cycle cannot exceed its appropriation —
      and a <strong>ledger</strong>: every cycle is a record of what it planned, why each item was chosen, and
      what it cost; every visit points back to the cycle that caused it. The schedule itself has provenance.
      And the plan always shows its <strong>horizon</strong> — "35,000 records remaining ≈ 700 cycles at this
      budget" — so the pace of a collection's enliteracy is a decision someone owns, never an accident.
      The pulse is also <strong>pressable</strong>: the <%= link_to "Heartbeat", heartbeat_path %> surface
      triggers one cycle and shows it beating — each visit landing on the ledger as it happens.
    </p>
    <p>
      And before any record is read, the collection <strong>shelf-reads itself</strong> — the practice
      every library knows. Each cycle runs a conservation survey up digital preservation's ladder:
      is the item <em>present</em> (the link resolves), <em>intact</em> (the file is valid),
      <em>extractable</em> (usable text came out)? A dead link with a cached copy still circulates —
      the library kept a surrogate; a record with no readable text is pulled from the tending queues
      so nothing is spent reading what cannot be read. What can't be probed is <em>intelligibility</em> —
      and there the tending loop itself is the instrument: records that read fine but never yield
      understanding surface as their own pile. A <strong>conservator</strong> reviews every pile and writes,
      in plain language, what's wrong and what staff must do to bring those records into the loop —
      the condition report becomes a work queue for people, and when a record is repaired, the next
      survey simply notices. Resolution is measured, never asserted.
    </p>
    <p>
      And the catalog <strong>audits itself</strong>. Each cycle, an examiner re-reads a random sample of
      claims against their sources and renders a verdict — supported, unsupported, contradicted — with
      humans confirming or overruling on the <%= link_to "Review", review_path %> page. The accuracy of
      the whole claim store is <strong>published, per facet and per tier</strong>, alongside the examiner's own
      calibration against its human reviewers. Verdicts never age out when a claim is replaced, so
      re-reading can never launder the number; and when a person corrects a wrong claim, the correction
      is locked — the model can never quietly overwrite a librarian.
    </p>

    <h2 id="the-reference-desk">The reference desk</h2>
    <p>
      An enliterated collection can be <em>asked</em>. The <%= link_to "Chat", conversation_path %>
      surface is not a search box wearing a chat skin — it's a <strong>reference interview</strong>.
      The desk triages a question, hands it to a grounded specialist when one is better placed to
      answer, reasons its reply while you watch the work, and <strong>cites the records it
      consulted</strong> inline — each citation a link back to the record itself. When it finishes it
      offers the next good questions, reasoned from the answer rather than drawn from a fixed list, so
      the inquiry continues by pointing — the way a good librarian hears the question behind your
      question.
    </p>
    <p>
      Its <strong>voice is yours to shape</strong>. Each desk carries an institutional register the
      engine owns and a <em>persona</em> a curator can edit, version, and roll back — the same
      authority control that governs the collection's vocabulary, now turned on how the desk speaks.
      And it is safe to hand someone the voice because <strong>behavior does not live in the
      words</strong>: what the desk may read, that it must ground every claim, that it shows its
      provenance — these are enforced by the engine's loop, not by the prompt. You can rewrite every
      line of a persona and never loosen a single guarantee.
    </p>
    <p>
      And the conversations themselves are <strong>kept</strong>. Each exchange is retained as a
      first-class record and can be replayed from its own event stream — so a good answer can be shown
      again without being re-run, and the collection can, in time, <strong>tend its own
      conversations</strong> the way it tends its records: the engine turning its attention on the one
      surface where it speaks. The thesis, applied to itself.
    </p>

    <h2 id="the-conscience-is-human">The conscience is human</h2>
    <p>
      At Burning Man there's a saying: if you make eye contact with trash, it's yours — not because you
      made it, because you <em>saw</em> it. The obligation doesn't come from perception; it comes from the
      relationship the gaze creates. Once you see it, you can't unsee it, and the world fills with things
      asking for grace.
    </p>
    <p>
      The tending system has no ethics. It has a schedule and a credit card. It runs because someone decided
      the output justified the cost; cancel the card and it stops. The <strong>conscience belongs to the
      person who saw the collection sitting dormant and couldn't look away</strong> — the one who can see the
      need and authorize the spend. Society funds a child's literacy with buildings and teachers' salaries.
      The enliteracy of a collection is the same shape: someone decides the tending is worth paying for. The
      engine is infrastructure. The decision is yours.
    </p>

    <h2 id="for-a-collection-like-this-one">For a collection like this one</h2>
    <p>
      A homeland-security thesis archive is exactly the case that rewards tending. Each thesis is a dense
      argument that took an author a year to make — and then it sits, findable by keyword, rarely read.
      Tended, every thesis declares what it contributes, what it found, where it's limited, who wrote it,
      and which other work it speaks to. The collection becomes a <strong>living body of scholarship</strong>
      that can be questioned as a whole, that surfaces the connections no single reader would find, and that
      grows sharper every time the loop runs. Dormant becomes legible; an archive becomes a colleague.
    </p>

    <h2 id="the-four-surfaces">The surfaces</h2>
    <div class="surfaces-grid">
      <div class="card">
        <span class="surface-title"><%= link_to "Status", root_path %></span>
        <span class="surface-desc">The self-portrait — per-facet health, the vocabulary it uses, the connection graph, and drill-down into any single tended record.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="surface-title"><%= link_to "Catalog", catalog_path %></span>
        <span class="surface-desc">The holdings, browsable — search by meaning, browse by subject heading, wander the open stacks; every card shows what the collection knows.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="surface-title"><%= link_to "Chat", conversation_path %></span>
        <span class="surface-desc">The reference desk — a governed reference interview that triages, routes to grounded specialists, streams its reasoning, and cites the records it consulted.</span>
      </div>
      <% if Enliterator.configuration.chat_persona_editing %>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="surface-title"><%= link_to "Desks", desks_path %></span>
        <span class="surface-desc">Shape the desk's voice — edit each desk's persona, versioned with rollback and reset-to-seed; the engine register and org chart stay code-owned and read-only.</span>
      </div>
      <% end %>
      <% if Enliterator.configuration.chat_retention %>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="surface-title"><%= link_to "Conversations", conversations_path %></span>
        <span class="surface-desc">The kept conversations — browse, label, and replay retained exchanges from their own event stream; the corpus the desk will learn to tend.</span>
      </div>
      <% end %>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="surface-title"><%= link_to "Requests", suggestions_path %></span>
        <span class="surface-desc">Govern the vocabulary — review the terms the model wants, approve / map / reject, and watch the loop converge.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="surface-title"><%= link_to "Review", review_path %></span>
        <span class="surface-desc">The human anchor — confirm, overrule, or correct the examiner's verdicts on sampled claims; the audit's ground truth.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="surface-title"><%= link_to "Contexts", contexts_path %></span>
        <span class="surface-desc">Collections within collections — the context tree, each lens's facets and members; the nav switcher views every surface through any of them.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="surface-title"><%= link_to "Atlas", atlas_path %></span>
        <span class="surface-desc">The collection, drawn — records, the entities their claims name, every edge carrying its provenance; replay it to watch the collection learn.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="surface-title"><%= link_to "Heartbeat", heartbeat_path %></span>
        <span class="surface-desc">The pulse, pressable — trigger one tending cycle and watch it live: the queue, the spend against its budget, every visit as it lands on the ledger.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="surface-title"><%= link_to "Settings", settings_path %></span>
        <span class="surface-desc">The configuration — the org chart of facets and tiers, the effective vocabulary, and how the considerer decides.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="surface-title">About</span>
        <span class="surface-desc">This page. What we're building and why — kept current as the engine grows.</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="about-colophon">
      Living document &middot; reflects Enliterator as of <strong>July 2026</strong> (v0.59 &mdash;
      a record whose source has changed stops inheriting its old reading: when an edit to the source
      triggers a re-tend, the reader is told the text has moved and re-derives each claim from the
      current words rather than confirming the prior one &mdash; the fix for a claim that went on saying
      &ldquo;improbable&rdquo; after its chapter had been rewritten to &ldquo;contingent,&rdquo; fresh
      but wrong &mdash; and the change signal can now be scoped per facet, so an edit that touches one
      dimension need not re-read them all; v0.58 &mdash;
      the first-impression diagnostic: <span class="mono">rake enliterator:first_impression</span>
      measures, in one number, how much a record&rsquo;s enliteration adds to a machine reader&rsquo;s
      first impression over the bare surrogate a catalog gives it &mdash; sampling records, generating
      a grounded question set, answering it under four reading conditions (abstract, catalog,
      abstract-plus-enliteration, raw source), blind-grading, and reporting the coverage and
      reliability lift with a canary that catches a leaked answer &mdash; the finding-aid thesis made
      falsifiable, that a stronger model cannot reason its way to knowledge that isn&rsquo;t in front
      of it; v0.57.2 &mdash;
      the heartbeat&rsquo;s budget box stops lying by omission: a value typed above the configured
      ceiling was silently clamped down to it, so raising it did nothing &mdash; now the form names
      the ceiling, warns live as you cross it, and the post-beat notice says when a request was
      clamped; v0.57 &mdash;
      the charter&rsquo;s telling half: the collection <em>introduces itself</em> &mdash; its proper
      noun, purpose, and audience, the extrinsic identity no synthesis can derive, told by its
      keepers as human-attributed claims on a one-row collection record, led with by every reader
      surface (the overview an agent reads first, the finding aid&rsquo;s header, the reference
      desk&rsquo;s own voice), with each still-untold field an open, named gap &mdash; the answer to
      the first external reader&rsquo;s complaint that the collection could report its skeleton but
      not say what it was; v0.57.1 &mdash; a transient provider-serialization quirk (a double-encoded
      tool-call array, ~7% of long indexing reads) stops making permanent facet holes: named
      honestly, auto-retried with every attempt&rsquo;s spend on the ledger; v0.56 &mdash;
      the topology declaration: a host tells the engine its collection&rsquo;s <em>shape</em> &mdash;
      the grouping that composes records into wholes (chapters into a book) &mdash; and the engine
      derives one context per whole (membership: the whole&rsquo;s full holdings, drafts included)
      and, when the collection declares itself an archive of sovereign works, reads each record
      against <em>its own whole</em> at tending time instead of the undifferentiated shelf &mdash;
      scoped by the host grouping itself, so a book&rsquo;s chapter meets its own book&rsquo;s
      chapters, never another&rsquo;s; v0.55 &mdash;
      the synthesized tendable: the engine&rsquo;s first <em>whole above records</em> &mdash; a host
      type that is a composite whole (a book made of its chapters) is tended by deliberate invocation
      and held out of the pacemaker and the corpus census, yet stays a real, drillable record whose
      book-level understanding still shows on every claim surface &mdash; &ldquo;the collection can
      think about itself,&rdquo; one level up; v0.54.1 &mdash;
      the review desk, finished: the evidence behind each proposal now names its source record by
      human title (not a uuid) and orders it in book position, and the per-record page shows full
      claim values instead of truncating them &mdash; the reviewer can finally read what they are
      judging; v0.54 &mdash;
      the review desk gives the reviewer what they need to decide: the full evidence behind each
      proposal &mdash; every record&rsquo;s reasoning and example, no truncation &mdash; is one click
      away, and a suggested mapping now shows what the target term means and what already folds onto it,
      so the fit can be judged before accepting; v0.53 &mdash;
      the review desk, reviewer-flow-first: each request card now leads with the considerer&rsquo;s
      recommended action &mdash; a suggested mapping puts a green Map first with the target already
      filled in, a suggested approval a green Approve &mdash; so a whole queue can be worked one click
      at a time, and the map target is a type-ahead over the vocabulary instead of a long dropdown;
      v0.52 &mdash;
      curator corrections: the standing vocabulary can now be re-adjudicated from the
      <%= link_to "authority file", vocabulary_path %> itself &mdash; re-route a variant onto a different
      preferred term, promote a variant to a preferred term, demote a preferred term, or merge a whole
      term and its variants into another &mdash; the work that previously required hand-editing the
      database; v0.51 &mdash;
      the <%= link_to "authority file", vocabulary_path %>: the standing controlled vocabulary drawn as a
      thesaurus &mdash; each preferred term with the variant terms folded onto it, ranked by how many it
      has gathered, so a curator can see the shape of the whole: a term absorbing variants from many
      facets, or a long tail of terms seen on a single record. The resolved companion to the Requests
      queue; v0.50 &mdash;
      the authority-control desk stops misleading the curator: the Map dropdown pre-fills the
      considerer&rsquo;s suggested target only when the considerer was confident enough to have applied it
      itself, a verdict that changes nothing now says so instead of reporting success, and a recommended
      target that is itself still pending explains that it must be approved before it can be mapped onto;
      v0.49 &mdash;
      the vocabulary desk stops blocking: the considerer reads the request field in batches and runs in
      the background, so &ldquo;Consider all requests&rdquo; returns at once and a live monitor shows it
      converge &mdash; a large queue no longer overruns a single giant call that times out; v0.47 &mdash;
      the atlas became a research instrument: alongside the orientation Overview, an Ego lens to explore
      around one record or entity &mdash; a ranked neighbor list beside the graph, an inspector showing a
      node&rsquo;s claims, provenance, and known gaps, and typed-edge filters by relation, confidence,
      audit, and depth, all sharing one selection; v0.46.1 &mdash;
      lacunae: the collection now records what it looked for and could not find &mdash; and why. When a
      required fact (an author, a date) comes back empty, the engine no longer files a blank claim that
      reads as a broken record &mdash; it opens a named gap, a known-unknown, diagnosed as to cause (the
      byline our extraction lost, a fact the document never carried, a name beyond recovery), and closes
      it the day a later reading supplies the value. A collection that can say not only what it knows but
      what it knows it is missing, and why; v0.45 &mdash;
      name authority control: the same person, written a dozen ways across the records
      (&ldquo;Jordan Avery,&rdquo; &ldquo;Jordan L. Avery,&rdquo; &ldquo;Jordan L. Avery
      (contractor)&rdquo;), now resolves to one authorized name, so a count is the person and not a
      spelling &mdash; the value-side twin of the vocabulary that tends itself, conservative by
      design (it folds the certain and holds the ambiguous, never merging two people); v0.44 —
      the desk can deliver: when the Reference Desk consults a record, it now names that record to
      the host as plain identity, so a federated front-end can turn &ldquo;what do you have on
      this?&rdquo; into a link to the catalog and, on request, the document itself &mdash; the desk
      stays read-only, it only surfaces; v0.41.2 —
      read-time warrant accrual: a reader now works with the vocabulary in hand, seeing the candidate
      terms other readers proposed and affirming one that fits rather than coining a synonym, so the
      controlled vocabulary converges where the reading happens; v0.41.1 —
      graceful bedrock unavailability: with all enliteration on bedrock and no fallback, an expired
      SSO session or a gateway timeout is a pause, not a failure — the heartbeat defers the work and
      resumes on the next beat; v0.41 —
      reset to seed: a desk returns to its registered persona, auditably — the persona editor,
      completed; v0.40 — the method, shipped: <em>enliterating-a-collection</em>, the practice of
      taking a collection from dormant to literate, encoded as a first-draft skill in the gem to be
      tended through every use; v0.39 — chat retention: every conversation kept as a first-class
      artifact and replayed from its own event stream, so the desk's conversations become tendable;
      v0.38 — the desk made testable: a per-desk step budget and a no-browser way to evaluate a desk
      as data; v0.37 — persona editing: each desk's voice is curator-editable, versioned, and
      reversible — code seeds, the store governs; v0.36 — the reference register: an engine-owned
      institutional voice beneath every desk's persona; v0.35 — the desk helps you ask: the agent
      reasons its own next questions, clickable; v0.34 — follow the stream: the answer auto-scrolls
      and the sources tuck away; v0.33 — the agentic answer streams token-by-token; v0.32 — a
      consulted record becomes a door back into the conversation; v0.31 — the reading room quiets:
      the chrome recedes as you talk and the desk shows it's thinking; v0.30 —
      actionable errors at the desk: when a turn fails, the reading room now tells you
      <em>what</em> broke and what to do about it &mdash; the exception, the tier it failed at,
      and a hint for the fix (a stale login, a slow tier) &mdash; shown in development, never
      leaked in production; v0.29 —
      the Reference Desk made legible: the agentic turn reads as a reference interview &mdash;
      a live work-trace, the answer, the records consulted &mdash; with provenance woven into
      the prose as inline citations you can follow, and the whole reading room lifted into a
      scholarly serif register; v0.28 —
      the Reference Desk: the chat becomes an agent that triages, routes to grounded specialists,
      and shows its provenance inline &mdash; opt-in behind <code>config.chat_federation</code>;
      v0.27 —
      the brief: the collection reports its own night — cycles, failures with their
      reasons, readings, governance motion — as one rake task and one agent tool; v0.26 —
      the MCP surface: conversational agents get the reading-room card — provenance,
      trajectory, and self-knowledge as queryable tools, with writes only through the
      governed queues; v0.25 —
      analytical cataloging: sections become tendable parts, a reading takes per-section
      notes the way a librarian reads, and the work-level understanding is re-synthesized
      from the notebook — deepening that supersedes in place; v0.24 the
      catalog: the holdings browsable at last — search by meaning, subject headings congruent
      with their click-throughs, the open-stacks wander; v0.23 every cycle
      ends on the ledger: orphaned cycles are reaped with their endings reconstructed from
      provenance; v0.22 portability: the enliteration moves between deployments instead of
      re-buying the inference; v0.21 the atlas: the collection drawn as a graph whose every edge
      carries its provenance, replayable in time; v0.20 the prepared finding aid; v0.19 one
      quiet component system; v0.18 the audit:
      the catalog measures its own accuracy, humans anchor the examiner; v0.17 condition; v0.16
      the pressable pulse; v0.15 the heartbeat; v0.13 contexts; v0.12 spoke the library's
      language). Not searchability conferred once — <strong>attention that compounds</strong>.
    </p>

  </div><%# /about-content %>
</div><%# /about-layout %>

<script>
(function () {
  // Scrollspy: highlights TOC links as sections enter the viewport.
  // Strategy: IntersectionObserver tracks which headings have passed the top of
  // the page; the most recently-passed heading (highest in document order but
  // not yet below the reading line) is the active one.
  // Respects prefers-reduced-motion for smooth scroll behaviour.

  var prefersReducedMotion = window.matchMedia &&
    window.matchMedia('(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)').matches;

  var headingIds = [
    'what-is-enliterator',
    'the-missing-word',
    'what-tended-means',
    'compounding-attention',
    'how-it-works',
    'the-pulse',
    'the-reference-desk',
    'the-conscience-is-human',
    'for-a-collection-like-this-one',
    'the-four-surfaces'
  ];

  // Smooth-scroll on TOC link click
  document.querySelectorAll('.about-toc a[href^="#"]').forEach(function (link) {
    link.addEventListener('click', function (e) {
      var targetId = link.getAttribute('href').slice(1);
      var target = document.getElementById(targetId);
      if (!target) return;
      e.preventDefault();
      target.scrollIntoView({
        behavior: prefersReducedMotion ? 'instant' : 'smooth',
        block: 'start'
      });
      history.pushState(null, '', '#' + targetId);
    });
  });

  // ── Scrollspy via getBoundingClientRect on scroll ─────────────────────────
  // This approach is robust regardless of section length: on every scroll we
  // find the last heading whose top edge is at or above 20% from the top of
  // the viewport, and activate it. Cheap because headingIds is tiny (8 items).

  var activeId = null;
  var THRESHOLD = 0.20; // heading must be within top 20% of viewport to activate

  function findActive() {
    var vh = window.innerHeight;
    var line = vh * THRESHOLD; // pixel offset — headings above this line are "past"
    var best = null;
    for (var i = 0; i < headingIds.length; i++) {
      var el = document.getElementById(headingIds[i]);
      if (!el) continue;
      var top = el.getBoundingClientRect().top;
      if (top <= line) {
        best = headingIds[i]; // keep updating — last one wins (furthest down doc)
      }
    }
    return best || headingIds[0];
  }

  function setActive(id) {
    if (id === activeId) return;
    activeId = id;
    document.querySelectorAll('.about-toc a').forEach(function (a) {
      if (a.getAttribute('href') === '#' + id) {
        a.setAttribute('aria-current', 'true');
      } else {
        a.removeAttribute('aria-current');
      }
    });
  }

  // Throttle scroll handler with requestAnimationFrame
  var ticking = false;
  function onScroll() {
    if (!ticking) {
      requestAnimationFrame(function () {
        setActive(findActive());
        ticking = false;
      });
      ticking = true;
    }
  }

  window.addEventListener('scroll', onScroll, { passive: true });

  // Set initial active state on load
  setActive(findActive());
})();
</script>
